Building on the modeling from my previous forecast [1], I've updated the script [2] to take in an estimated planned retirement probability for Justice Breyer (which I estimate is appoximately 1/3) and then combine it with my estimated probabilities of an unplanned vacancy within the supreme court justices which I described in my previous forecast. Since the probabilities are multiplied together to get the estimate, the order doesn't matter, but, logically, it is important to conceptualize that Breyer's planned retirement would reduce the chances of his unplanned vacancy and his unplanned vacancy would reduce the chances of his planned retirement, so this is accounted for. Furthermore, I apply a scalar to account for the time left until the expiration of the question where the probability of a vacancy gets lower and lower as the deadline approaches. That covers modeling the "No" probability. For the next iteration, I'll model the two buckets of the "Yes" probability, but for now I'll say that I think the chances are high that a replacement justice would be confirmed if there is an opening and sufficient time. Justices are typically loathe to retire without a clear replacement. With the low approval rating of the President and predicted upcoming turmoil in Congressional elections that may result in power changes and contentious hearings, barring a health crisis, it is unlikely that Justice Breyer will feel comfortable retiring.

According to the Washington Post, twice as many justices (six) retired since 1990 as died in office (three). Three of the six that retired were 83 or older. Breyer is the second longest serving justice, and will be 84 this year. He may have been convinced to retire by watching what happened when Ruth Bader Ginsburg passed away and her seat was filled by a conservative Republican.

I think three factors suggest J Breyer will not retire (or die) this year. First, he began the current term and has said he’s not yet decided. That suggests he isn’t ready to say he will depart when the session ends in June. Second, if his retirement is intended to promote the democrats’ chances of confirming a like-minded nominee, there is no guarantee that will happen. The Senate’s holds a majority only due to the vote of the VP, and as we have seen both Senators Manchin and Sinema have derailed key administration priorities. Justice Breyer’s replacement therefore would either be dictated by either one of these (or another senator), and the Justice (or the administration) might be worried about the idea of each of fifty senators holding the key to this seat. Likewise, if a D senator dies or becomes incapacitated after Breyer retires, the Rs would hold the majority. I didn’t look it up, but my guess is there are many senators that are older or less healthy than he is. Point 3: Since 1987, 3 Justices died on the bench while 4 retired, which tracks a general near 50/50 trend so it is not like there is any historical tradition that suggests he should leave.

There are two main ways for a vacancy on the US Supreme court to occur: death or retirement. It's possible for a justice to be impeached and removed, but that seems highly unlikely. Calculating the probability of death can be done using the social security website, which has the probability of death in the next year by age and gender: https://www.ssa.gov/oact/STATS/table4c6.html
